Consider, for example, a Poisson process with \(\mathcal{E}=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}\), that generates points \(x=(r,w)\) according to the mean measure

\[\begin{equation} \mu\{(r,\infty)\times (w,\infty)\}=\frac{1}{r}\times \Phi(-\frac{1}{\sigma}\log w - \frac{\sigma}{2}), \qquad{r,w>0} \end{equation}\]

where \(\sigma>0\) and \(\Phi\) is the standard normal distribution function.

This corresponds to setting \(\mathcal{P}=\{ (R_i, W_i): i=1,2,\ldots \}\), where \(E_i \stackrel{\text{iid}}{\sim}\text{exp}(1)\), and \(W_i = \text{exp}(\sigma \varepsilon_i - \frac{\sigma^2}{2})\), where \(\varepsilon\stackrel{\text{iid}}{\sim} \mathcal{N}(0,1)\), indpendnet of the \(E_{i}\). Note that \(E(W_i)=1\).

The mean measure has an intensity function \(\dot{\mu}\) given by its derivative at the upper right corner of a rectangle \((r', r)\times (w', w)\), i.e.,

\[\begin{align} \dot{\mu}(r,w) &= \frac{\partial^2 \mu \{ (r',r)\times (w',w) \}}{\partial r \partial w}\nonumber\\ &= \frac{\partial^2}{\partial r \partial w}\{ \mu(r',w')-\mu(r,w')-\mu(r',w)+\mu(r,w) \}\\ &= \frac{1}{r^2}\times \frac{1}{\sigma w}\phi(-\frac{1}{\sigma}\log w -\frac{\sigma}{2}), \qquad{r, w >0,} \end{align}\]

where we have written \(\mu(r,w)=\mu\{ (r,\infty)\times (w,\infty) \}\) and so forth, and \(\phi\) denotes the standard normal density function. Note that \(\mu(\mathcal{A})\) equals the integral of \(\dot{\mu}\) over \(\mathcal{A}\).

A key role in constructing models for spatial extremes is played by the mapping theorem.

Theorem 1.1 (mapping theorem) Under mild conditions states that if a function \(g\) does not create atoms, then \(\mathcal{P}^{*}=g(\mathcal{P})\) also follows a Poisson process.

As a simple example we might take \(g(r,w)=rw\), corresponding to setting \(Q_i = R_i W_i\). Clearly \(\mu[ \{ (r,\frac{q}{r}): r>0 \} ]=0\) for each \(q>0\), so this transformation does not create atoms. We obtain the mean measure of this new Poisson process by noting that \(Q=RW>q\) if and only if \(R>\frac{q}{W}\), and the corresponding set \(\mathcal{A}_{q}=\{(r,w):rw>q\}\) has measure

\[\begin{align} \mu(\mathcal{A}_q) &= \int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{1}{\sigma w}\phi(-\frac{1}{\sigma}\log w -\frac{\sigma}{2})\int_{r=\frac{q}{w}}^{\infty}\frac{1}{r^2}drdw\nonumber\\ &=\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{1}{\sigma w}\phi(-\frac{1}{\sigma}\log w -\frac{\sigma}{2})\Big[ -\frac{1}{r} \Big]_{\frac{q}{w}}^{\infty}dw\nonumber\\ &= \frac{1}{q}E(W)=\frac{1}{q}, \qquad{q>0}. \tag{1.1} \end{align}\]

Hence the process with points \(Q_i = R_iW_i\) is also Poissonian, with the same mean measure as the \(R_i\). Note that the calculation leading to (1.1) requires only that \(W\) is positive and satisfies \(E(W)=1\).

The restriction of \(\mathcal{P}\) to a subset \(\mathcal{E}'\) \(\mathcal{E}\) clearly also follows a Poisson process, with mean measure \(\mu'(\mathcal{A})=\mu(\mathcal{E}'\cap \mathcal{A})\). For example, if we let \(\mathcal{E}=(0,\infty)\), consider \(R_1, R_2, \ldots,\) and let \(\mathcal{E}'=(z',\infty)\) for some \(z'>0\), then we retain only those poins \(R_i\), exceeding \(z'\). As \(\mu(\mathcal{E}')=\frac{1}{z'}\) is finite, those \(R_i\) can be generated by first simulating a Poisson variable \(N'\) with mean \(\frac{1}{z'}\), and if \(N'=n\), simulating \(n\) independent variables on the interval \((z',\infty)\) with survivor function \(\frac{z'}{z}\); these Pareto variables have probability density function \(\frac{z'}{z^2}\) (\(z>z'\)).

1.2 Classical results

To connect the above rather abstract discussion with classical results for maxima of a random sample \(X_1, \ldots, X_n\), note for any real \(b_n\) and positive \(a_n\) that

\[\begin{equation} \frac{\max (X_1, \ldots, X_n)-b_n}{a_n}\leq y \Leftrightarrow N_n\{ (y,\infty) \}=0, \tag{1.2} \end{equation}\]

where \(N_n(\mathcal{A})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}I\{\frac{(X_j-b_n)}{a_n}\in\mathcal{A}\}\) for \(\mathcal{A}\subset \mathbb{R}\); \(N_n(\mathcal{A})\) has a binomial distribution. If the extremal types theorem applies to \(X_1, \ldots, X_n\), then there exist sequences \(\{b_n\}\) and \(\{a_n\}>0\) such that limiting probability of (1.2) is a generalized extreme value (GEV) form, and this implies that the binomial random variables \(N_n\{(y,\infty\}\) satisfy

\[\begin{equation} \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}P[N_n \{ (y,\infty\}=0]=\exp\Bigg\{ - \Big( 1 + \xi \frac{y-\eta}{\tau} \Big)_{+}^{-\frac{1}{\xi}} \Bigg\}, \tag{1.3} \end{equation}\]

where \(a_+ = \max(a,0)\) and \(\xi,\eta\in\mathbb{R}\) and \(\tau > 0\) are respectively shape, location and scale parameters. Thus as \(n\rightarrow\infty\), the point processes \(\mathcal{P}_n = \{\frac{(X_n-b_n)}{a_n}: j=1,\ldots, n \}\) converge to a limiting Poisson process \(\mathcal{P}\) with mean measure \(\mu\{(y,\infty) \}=\{1+ \xi\frac{y-\eta}{\tau} \}_{+}^{-\frac{1}{\xi}}\). The limiting generalized extreme-value distribution for the maximum corresponds to the probability that the set \((y,\infty)\cap \mathcal{P}\) contains no points, a void probability of \(\mathcal{P}\). This distribution arises as a limit, and thus provides an approximation that should improve as \(n\) increases. Likewise the Poisson process approximately may be poor unless \(n\) is sufficiently large.

The process \(\mathcal{P}\) can be transformed to have mean measure \(\frac{1}{z}\) on \(\mathbb{R}_{+}\) by setting \(z=\{1+ \xi\frac{y-\eta}{\tau} \}_{+}^{-\frac{1}{\xi}}\), and fitting (1.3) to sample maxima can be regarded as finding the \(\eta, \tau\), and \(\xi\) that best achieve this. On this transformed scale the maximum has limiting distribution function \(\exp(-\frac{1}{z})\) \((z>0)\); this, the stnadrad Frechet distribution, corresponds to (1.3) with \(\eta=\tau=\xi=1\).

The generalized extreme-value distribution is max-stable; in the case of independent standard Frechet variables \(Z, Z_1, \ldots, Z_n\), this means that

\[\begin{equation} \frac{1}{n}\max(Z_1,\ldots, Z_n)\stackrel{D}{=}Z, \qquad{n=1,2,\ldots} \tag{1.4} \end{equation}\]

where \(\stackrel{D}{=}\) means has the same distribution as; these equalities correspond to setting \(b_n=0\) and \(a_n=n\) in (1.2).

The generalized Pareto distribution (GPD) emerges on noting that large values of the transformed original variables \(Z_j = \{ 1+ \xi \frac{(X_j - \eta)}{\tau} \}_{+}^{\frac{1}{\xi}}\) approximately follow a Poisson process on \(\mathbb{R}_{+}\) with the mean measure \(\frac{1}{z}\). Those points for which \(X_j > u\), or equivalently \(Z_j > \{ 1+\xi\frac{(u-\eta)}{\tau} \}_{+}^{\frac{1}{\xi}}\), for some high threshold \(u\), satisfy

\[\begin{align} P(X_j>y | X_j > u) &= \frac{P(X_j >y)}{P(X_j>u)}\nonumber\\ &\stackrel{\cdot}{=} \frac{\{ 1+\xi \frac{(y-\eta)}{\tau} \}_{+}^{-\frac{1}{\xi}}}{\{1+\xi \frac{(u-\eta)}{\tau} \}_{+}^{-\frac{1}{\xi}}}\nonumber\\ &= \Big( 1+ \xi \frac{y-u}{\sigma_u} \Big)_{+}^{-\frac{1}{\xi}}, \qquad{y>u},\nonumber \end{align}\]

where \(\sigma_{u} = \tau + \xi(u-\eta)\); this yields the generalized Pareto distribution, which is therefore the limiting model for threshold exceedances that corresponds to fitting (1.3) to maxima. This ditribution is threshold-stable: it is easy to check that the distribution of each \(X_j\), conditional on the event \(X_j > u'>u\), is also generalized Pareto, with the same shape parameter \(\xi\). Like the GEV and Poisson process, the GPD approximation stems from a limit and may be poor if the threshold \(u\) is too low.

1.3 Spectral representation

Spectral representation Laurens de Haan (2006) Theorem 9.6.1 . Morris, Reich, and Thibaud (2019) max-stable process countable number of spatial process . process Gaussian process ((Schlather 2002)), log-Gaussian process ((Kabluchko, Schlather, and Haan 2009)) .

The Poisson process allows a general discussion of the classical extreme-value models in terms of a spectral representation, to be described below. This applies to the univariate setting, the multivariate setting, and to the functional setting, which we now describe.

Max-stability is the key property of the generalized extreme-value distribution that underpins ( ) its use for the estimation of rare event probabilities. On the standard Frechet scale this may be expressed to (1.4), and the analogous equation for max-stable process, which generalize the GEV to multivariate and functional settings, is

\[\begin{equation} \frac{1}{n}\max(Z_1(x),\ldots, Z_n(x))\stackrel{D}{=}Z(x), \qquad{x\in\mathcal{X},n=1,2,\ldots ;} \tag{1.5} \end{equation}\]

we require (1.5) to hold for the entire process \(\{Z(x): x\in\mathcal{X}\}\). When \(\mathcal{X}\) is a finite set, this corresponds to the max-stability of the multivariate extreme-value distributions.

To generalize our previous discussion, we extend the Poisson process \((R,W)\) so that \(\{W(x): x\in\mathcal{X}\}\) is a random process taking values in a suitable space of functions, with \(W(x)\geq 0\) and \(E\{W(x)\}=1\) for each \(x\). The topology on the function space, and the distribution of \(W\), must be sufficiently rich that the measure of \((R,W)\) remains non-atomic. Despite this added complexity, we continue to use the term points for \((R,W)\) and \(Q(x)=RW(x)\).

Any max-stable process may then be constructed through the spectral representation,

\[\begin{equation} Z(x)=\sup_{i=1}^{\infty}Q_{i}(x), \qquad{x\in\mathcal{X},} \tag{1.6} \end{equation}\]

where \(Q_i(x)=R_iW_i(x)\), with the \(R_i\) defined as before and the \(W_i(x)\) independent replicates of \(W(x)\) independent of the \(R_i\). Then the point \(Q_i(x)\) may be interpreted as the \(i\)-th event, whose overall scale and profile are respectively \(R_i\) and \(W_i(x)\).

Since \(W(x)\geq 0\) and \(E\{W(x)\}=1\) for each \(x\), the mean measure for \(Q(x)=RW(x)\) is (1.1), so \(P\{Z(x) \leq z\}=\exp(-\frac{1}{z})\) for each \(x\); the max-stable process is then called simple.

It may be shown that any max-stable process may be constructed via (1.6), though the representation is not unique. Recal that in deriving (1.1), we saw that the same mean measure, and hence the same Poisson process, would have been obtained for any positive random variable \(W\) with unit expectation. This non-uniqueness may be exploited to provide efficient simulation algorithms.

To obtain the joint distribution of \(Z(x)\) for values of \(x\) lying in a subset \(\mathcal{D}\) of \(\mathcal{X}\), note that the event \(\{Z(x) \leq z(x): x\in\mathcal{D}\}\) occurs if and only if \(R_i W_i(x)\leq z(x)\) for all \(x\in\mathcal{D}\) and all \(i\), and this is equivalent to \(R_i \leq \inf_{x\in\mathcal{D}}\frac{z(x)}{W_i(x)}\) \((i=1,2,\ldots)\). In terms of the corresponding Poisson process this implies that the set

\[\{(r,w): rw(x)\leq z(x), x\in\mathcal{D}\}^{c} = \Bigg\{(r,w): r> \inf_{x\in\mathcal{D}}\frac{z(x)}{w(x)} \Bigg\},\]

where superscript \(c\) denotes complement, is void. The measure of this set may be expressed as

\[\begin{equation} \int \nu (dw) \int_{\inf_{x\in\mathcal{D}}\{\frac{z(x)}{w(x)} \}}\frac{dr}{r^2}=E\Big[ sup_{x\in\mathcal{D}} \Big\{ \frac{W(x)}{z(x)}\Big\} \Big]=V\{z(x): x\in\mathcal{D}\}, \tag{1.7} \end{equation}\]

say, where the expectation is over the measure \(\nu\) of \(W\), called the angular measure. Thus the required probability for \(Z(x)\) is a void probability of the Poisson process defined by \(Q(x)=RW(x)\), for \(x\in\mathcal{D}\), and so

\[\begin{equation} P\{Z(x)\leq z(x),x\in\mathcal{D}\}=\exp[-V\{z(x):x\in\mathcal{D} \}]. \tag{1.8} \end{equation}\]

If \(\mathcal{D}\) is finite, then this probability equals expression (8.5) in Alan Gelfand (2019); it equals the standard Frechet distribution \(\exp\{-\frac{1}{z(x)}\}\), \(z(x)>0\), for a singleton \(\mathcal{D} = \{x\}\).

The exponent function \(V\) plays a central role in inference and modelling. Since \(Z(x)\leq z(x)\) \((x\in\mathcal{D})\) if and only if all the \(Q_i(x)=R_iW_i(x)\) fall into the set \(\{ (r,w):rw(x)\leq z(x), x\in\mathcal{D} \}\), the measure of the Poisson process with points \(Q_i(x)\) is determined by setting

\[\mu[\{ q:q(x)\leq z(x), x\in\mathcal{D}^{c} \}]=V\{z(x):x\in\mathcal{D}\};\]

thus (1.8) is the void probability of \(\{q: q(x) \leq z(x), x\in\mathcal{D}\}^{c}\) for the Poisson process.

The case \(\mathcal{D}=\{x_{1}, \ldots, x_{D}\}\) is particularly important, because in practice, data are observed only on finite sets, and inference must therefore be based on observations of \(Z(x_1),\ldots, Z(x_D)\). Writing \(z(x_d)=z_d\) for simplicity, we let

\[ V(z_1,\ldots, z_D)=\mu(\mathcal{A}_z), \qquad{z_1,\ldots, z_D>0,} \]

where \(\mathcal{A}_z\) is the component of \([0,z_1]\times \cdots \times [0,z_D]\) in \(\mathcal{E}=[0,\infty)^{D}\backslash \{0\}\); the origin cannot be included because the limiting Poission process gives infinite measure for sets that contain it.

Expression (1.7) implies that \(V\) is homogeneous of order \(-1\), i.e.,

\[ V\{a z(x): x\in\mathcal{D} \}=\frac{1}{a}V\{z(x):x\in\mathcal{D}\}, \qquad{a>0.} \]

The max-stability (1.5) is easily established, because the event \(\frac{1}{n}\max\{ (Z_1(x), \ldots, Z_n(x)) \}\leq z(x)\) is equivalent to \(Z_j(x) \leq nz(x)\) \((j=1,\ldots, n)\), and since the \(Z_j(x)\) are independent, this occurs with probability

\[\begin{align*} (e^{[-V\{nz(x):x\in\mathcal{D}\}]})^{n} &= (e^{[-\frac{1}{n}V\{z(x):x\in\mathcal{D}\}]})^{n}\\ &= e^{[-V\{z(x):x\in\mathcal{D}\}]}. \end{align*}\]

If we set \(z(x)=z\), then the homogeneity of \(V\) yields

\[\begin{equation} P\{Z(x)\leq z, x\in\mathcal{D}\}=P\Big\{ \max_{x\in\mathcal{D}}Z(x) \leq z \Big\}=e^{-\frac{\theta_{\mathcal{D}}}{z}}, \qquad{z>0,} \tag{1.9} \end{equation}\]

where extremal coefficient \(\theta_{D}\) equals \(V\) evaluated with \(z(x)\equiv 1\) \((x\in\mathcal{D})\). Hence \(\max_{x\in\mathcal{D}}Z(x)\) has a Frechet distibution; its parameter \(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) can be shown to lie between \(1\) and \(|\mathcal{D}|\). These bounds respectively correspond to perfect dependence and complete independence of the components of \(Z(x)\). In particular, if \(\mathcal{D} =\{x_1,\ldots, x_D\}\), then \(1\leq \theta_{\mathcal{D}}\leq D\), with smaller values indicating stronger dependence of the extremes. Like the variogram, emprical estiamtes of \(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) are useful for explanatory purpose and for checking the adequacy of fitted models.

set.seed(2)
x <- seq(-5, 5, length = 1000)
n.block <- 100

Y <- sqrt(2 * pi) * pmax(rgp(n.block, x, range = 1, smooth = 1.99999), 0)
poisson <- 1 / cumsum(rexp(n.block))

tmp <- poisson * Y
Z <- apply(tmp, 2, max)

par(mar = c(4, 5, 0.5, 0.5), ps = 14, mfrow = c(1, 2))
matplot(x, t(tmp), col = "grey", lty = 1, type = "l",
        ylab = expression(zeta[i] * Y[i](x)))
lines(x, Z, lty = 1)

fun <- function(x) any(x == Z)

idx <- apply(tmp, 1, fun)

col <- c("blue", "red")[1 + idx]
matplot(x, t(tmp), col = col, lty = 1, type = "l",
        ylab = expression(varphi(x)))

1.4 Spatial extremes for exceedances

Max-stable processes provide models for quantities such as annual maximum rainfall at a number of sites in a region, but in some applications it is preferable to model individual extreme events. In terms of the discussion above, this requires deciding which of the \(Q_i (x)\) are to be regarded as extreme, and then basing inference on them, so we need to restrict the Poisson process \(\{Q_i(x)\}\) to some suitable set \(\mathcal{E}'\), for example by taking \(\mathcal{E}'=\{q:\rho(q)>1 \}\) for some risk functional \(\rho\). We might, for example, take

\[ \rho_1 (Q)=\sup_{x\in\mathcal{D}}\frac{Q(x)}{z(x)}, \rho_2 (Q) = \inf_{x\in\mathcal{D}}\frac{Q(x)}{z(x)}, \rho_3(Q)=\int_{\mathcal{D}}\frac{Q(x)}{z(x)}dx, \]

corresponding respectively to events that exceed a threshold function \(z(x)\) at at least one site in \(\mathcal{D}\), those that exceed \(z(x)\) everywhere in \(\mathcal{D}\) and those for which the average of \(\frac{Q(x)}{z(x)}\) over \(\mathcal{D}\) is sufficiently large. Thus the type of rare event selected can be tailored to the problem.

Some care is needed in the choice of \(\mathcal{E}'\), since likelihood inference involves the integral \(\mu(\mathcal{E}')\), which must be both finite and capable of being computed rapidly. If the risk functional satisfies \(\rho(aQ)=a\rho(Q)\) for \(a>0\), then \(\rho(Q)>1\) implies that \(R\rho(W)>1\), and then the argument leading to (1.1) can be extended to show that \(\mu(\mathcal{E}')=E\{\rho(W)\}\) depends only on the distribution of \(W\).

1.5.5 Other spatial extreme models

Max-stable processes may be modified in various ways. For example, skew-normal and skew-t processes can be used, rather than Gaussian or t-processe, and these may be useful when asymmetries are present (Beranger, Padoan, and Sisson 2016).

Another extension is multiplication by the indicator of a random compact set \(\mathcal{B}\) independent of \(W(\cdot)\), resulting in

\[W_{\mathcal{B}}(x)= W(x) \frac{I(x\in\mathcal{B})}{E(|\mathcal{B}|)}, \qquad{x\in\mathcal{X},}\]

where the expectation \(E(|\mathcal{B}|)\) must be finite in order to ensure that \(E\{W_{\mathcal{B}}(x)\}\equiv 1\). If we write \(\alpha(x_1, x_2)=P(x_1, x_2\in\mathcal{B})\), then it is straightforward to check that the corresponding exponent function is

\[\{1-\alpha(x_1, x_2) \}\Bigg(\frac{1}{z_1} + \frac{1}{z_2} \Bigg)+\alpha(x_1,x_2)V(z_1,z_2).\qquad{z_1,z_2>0.}\]

Thus if, for example \(\mathcal{B}\) is a disk of fixed diameter \(L\) centered at a point uniformly distributed on \(\mathcal{X}\), then \(x_1\) and \(x_2\) cannot both lie in \(\mathcal{B}\) when \(\|x_1 - x_2\| > L\), and \(Z(x_1)\) and \(Z(x_2)\) must be independent, whereas if \(x_1 \approx x_2\), then the exponent function will almost be that of the max-stable process based on \(W\). Huser and Davison (2013) use this idea to model extreme hourly rainfall; their random sets are stylized representations of the space-time extent of rainfall cells, each containing an independent process \(W(x)\).

Yet more processes may be constructed by letting \(W(x)=\frac{f(x;Y)}{f_y(Y)}\), where \(Y\) has density \(f_y\) on some space \(\mathcal{Y}\), and \(\int_{\mathcal{Y}} f(x;y)dy=1\) for each \(x\). The simplest such model, the Smith process, has \(\mathcal{Y}=\mathcal{X}=\mathbb{R}^{k}\), \(f_y(y)\) an arbitrary density supported on \(\mathbb{R}^k\) and \(f(x;y)=\phi_k(x-y;\Omega)\), where \(\phi_k(\cdot;\Omega)\) is the \(k\)-variate Gaussian density with covraince matrix \(\Omega\). The corresponding random functions \(Q(x)=RW(x)\) consist of \(k\)-variate Gaussian densities centered at random points of \(\mathbb{R}^{k}\), whose shape is determined by \(\Omega\) and whose maximum height is determined by \(R\) and \(|\Omega|\). These and similar processes obtained by using other standard probability density functions are typically too smooth to be realistic in applications.

2.4 Asymptotic independence in spatial extremes

Most of the models described aboe presuppose that the transformed extremes of the phenomenon under investigation are asymptotically dependent, i.e.,

\[\begin{equation} \lim_{z\rightarrow\infty}P\{Z(x_2)>z|Z(x_1)>z \}=2-\theta(x_1,x_2)>0, \qquad{x_1,x_2\in\mathcal{X},} \tag{2.3} \end{equation}\]

where \(\theta(x_1,x_2)=V(1,1)\) is the exponent function corresponding to \(Z(x_1)\) and \(Z(x_2)\). This implies that dependence between \(Z(x_1)\) and \(Z(x_2)\) persists even for very rare events, since the conditional probability of a rare event at \(x_2\), given the occurrence of an equally rare event at \(x_1\), remains non-zero as \(z\rightarrow\infty\). An alternative, which arises if \(V(z_1, z_2)=\frac{1}{z_1} + \frac{1}{z_2}\) is that extremes are exactly independent, but this is not a useful model because data alamost always show some degree of dependence.

An intermediate possibility is needed, whereby the limit in (2.3) is zero, but the conditional probability decreases as \(z\rightarrow\infty\). This is often plausible from physical arguments and is common in applications, of which it can be an important feature. Such asymptotic independence models are a topic of current research.

2.5 Exploratory procedures for spatial extremes

Simple nonparametric estimation procedures are valuable for initial analysis and for checking the validity of fitted models. Most are based on pairs of extremal obaservations, which offer direct insight into the dependence structure of the data, in analogy with quantities such as the variogram of classical geostatistics, which is defined in terms of the average squared difference between observations.

Since extremal observations need not possess moments, a rank-based approach is preferable. Suppose that observations \(Z_1\equiv Z(x_1)\) and \(Z_2\equiv Z(x_2)\) at sites \(\mathcal{D}=\{x_1, x_2\}\in\mathcal{X}\) arise from a simple max-stable process. A natural measure of the dependence between \(Z_1\) and \(Z_2\) is the extremal coefficient \(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) defined in (1.9); we have \(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\in [1,2]\), with smaller values corresponding to stronger dependence, so we can expect \(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) to increase as the distance \(\|x_1-x_2\|\) grows.

Estimation of \(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) may be based on the F-madogram,

\[ \psi_{\mathcal{D}}=\frac{1}{2}E\{ |F(Z_1) - F(Z_2)| \}, \]

where \(F(z)=e^{-\frac{1}{z}}\) \((z>0)\) is the standard Frechet distribution. Since \(|a-b|=2\max(a,b)-a-b\), and the distribution functions of \(Z_1, Z_2\) and \(\max(Z_1, Z_2)\) are respectively \(F(z)\), \(F(z)\) and \(e^{-\frac{\theta_{\mathcal{D}}}{z}}\) \((Z>0)\), it is straightforward to check that \(\phi_{\mathcal{D}}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}-1)}{(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}+1)}\) and therefore that

\[ \theta_{\mathcal{D}} = \frac{1+2\psi_{\mathcal{D}}}{1-2\psi_{\mathcal{D}}}. \]

An estimator \(\hat{\theta}_{\mathcal{D}}\) based on independent pairs \((Z_{1,1}, Z_{2,1}), \ldots, (Z_{1,n}, Z_{2,n})\) may be obtained by replacing \(F(Z_1)\) by the rank estimator \(\frac{R_{1,j}}{n+1}\) \((j=1,\ldots,n)\), where \(R_{1,j}\) is the rank of \(Z_{1,j}\) among \(Z_{1,1},\ldots, Z_{1,n}\), and likewise with \(F(Z_2)\), and then replacing \(\psi_{\mathcal{D}}\) by \(\frac{1}{2n(n+1)}\sum_{j=1}^{n}|R_{1,j}-R_{2,j}|\), its empirical counterpart.

If the underlying process is stationary, then \(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) depends only on \(h=x_1-x_2\), so a plot of the \(\hat{\theta}_{\mathcal{D}}\) for all possible pairs of points \(\mathcal{D}\) can be smoothed or binned and used for dignostic or confirmatory purposes. As in the classical case, some care must be taken in interpreting such plots, since data from \(D\) underlying sites yield a cloud of\(\frac{D(D-1)}{2}\) correlated estiamtes \(\hat{\theta}_{\mathcal{D}}\); moreover these empirical estimates may be very variable.

The anticipated increase in \(\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) with \(\|x_1-x_2\|\) makes a natural analogy with the variogram, but since \(P(Z_2>z|Z_1>z)\sim 2- \theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) as \(z\rightarrow\infty\), the quantity \(2-\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) may be interpreted as the probability of a large event at \(x_2\) given a correspondingly large event at \(x_1\).

A plot of \(2-\hat{\theta}_{\mathcal{D}}\) against distance is known as an extremogram, analogous to the correlogram of classical time series analysis, and has been proposed for use particularly with time series; resampling can be used to gauge which probabilities are indistinguishable from zero. Cross-extremograms or extremes of two or more series can also be defined, but like cross-correlograms, they are vulnerable to spurious correlations for which allowance must be made.

Th conditional probability \(2-\theta_{\mathcal{D}}\) has a natural interpretation for asymptotically dependent processes, but equals zero for asymptotically independent processes, whatever their rate of tail decay, so it is natural to seek a measure of asymptotic independence.

As many standard models are based on underying Gaussian processes, which are defined in terms of their first and second moments, standard fitting procedures will tend to match these to the data, either explicitly or implicitly. We might therefore expect theoretical and emprical estimates of pairwise quantities, such as the extremal coefficient \(\theta(h)\) of two sites a distance \(h\) apart, to match well enough to make model failure more difficult to detect. This suggests using higher-order, in addition to pairwise, quantities for checking model fit. For example, if \(\mathcal{D}=\{x_1, \ldots, x_D\}\) is a subset of sites, then it is easy to see that \(\max_{x\in\mathcal{D}}Z(x)\) has the Frechet distribution \(e^{-\frac{\theta_{\mathcal{D}}}{z}}\). Thus we might compare quantities of the observed maxima for \(\mathcal{D}\) with those from a fitted model, for sets \(\mathcal{D}\) that are spatially close or sptially far-flung; if the fitted model is adequate, the empirical and simulated distributions should match. Similarly, empricial probabilities of certain spatial events invoving more than two sites could be compared with estimates based on the model.

2.6 Inference of spatial extremes

Although there is a growing literature on non-parametric inference for extremal processes, parametric modelling is most used in applications. One reason for this is that it is usually more straightforward to interpret a parametric model, and a second is that a common goal of fitting such processes to data is the estimation of rare event probabilities. Typically this is performed by Monte Carlo simulation from one or more fitted models, which may be easier for a parametric model.

Statistical estimation for extreme values is always subject to mis-specification bias, since the classes of models fitted are typically based on asymptotic arguments that do not apply to the data themselves. It can be hard to detect lack of fit, because extremal models tend to be rather flexible and power for goodness-of fit assessment is limited owing to the small number of extreme events. Moreover the uncertainty surrounding extrapolation to events even rarer than those already observed is typically so large that bias is a secondary consideration. It is essential to assess the sensitivity of conclusions both to the choice of the model and to the degree of extremeness of the data: this entails checking that the fitted models do not change greatly when the threshold or block size is varied over a reasonable range.

Below we focus on likelihood-based estimation, but other proposals include robust estimation based directly on the joint distribution function, approximate Bayesian computation, and score-based methods.

Most of the discussion above has presupposed that the data have been transformed to the standard Frechet scale, but in practice this transformation should be built into the data analysis. For example, if annual maxima at points \(\mathcal{D}=\{x_1,\ldots, x_D\}\subset\mathcal{X}\) are available, then it will often be reasonable to suppose that their marginal distributions are generalized extreme-value with location, scale, and shape parameters \(\eta(x)\), \(\tau(x)\), and \(\xi(x)\) that vary smoothly over \(\mathcal{X}\) as functions of parameters \(\varphi\). Often we express \(\eta(x)\) and \(\log \tau(x)\) as linear combinations of basis functions and explanatory variables such as altitude, but assume that $(x) is constant, since variation in the shape parameter can be hard to detect and the value of \(\xi\) may be seen as an intrinsic aspect of the phenomenon being modelled. Since we can write

\[ Z(x;\varphi)=[1+\xi(x;\varphi)\frac{\{ Y(x)-\eta(x;\varphi) \}}{\tau(x;\varphi)} ]_{+}^{\frac{1}{\xi(x;\varphi)}}, \]

where \(Y(x)\) is the observed maximum at \(s\) and \(Z(x,\varphi)\) has a standard Frechet distribution, the joint probability density function of \(Y(x_1),\ldots, Y(x_D)\) can be written in terms of the standardized variables

\[ z(x_d;\varphi)=[1+\xi(x_d ;\varphi)\frac{\{ y_d -\eta(x_d ;\varphi) \}}{\tau(x_d ;\varphi)} ]_{+}^{\frac{1}{\xi(x_d ;\varphi)}}, \qquad{d=1,\ldots, D,} \]

as

\[\begin{equation} f_{Z(x_1),\ldots, Z(x_D)}\{z(x_1;\varphi), \ldots, z(x_D;\varphi)l\theta \}\times \prod_{d=1}^{D}\frac{dz(x_d;\varphi)}{d y_d} \tag{2.4} \end{equation}\]

where \(\theta\) represents parameters in the joint distribution of the \(Z\)s and the second term is a Jacobian.

Maximum likelihood estimation will involve maximizing a product of expressions of the form (2.4), for example with a term for each different year of observed maxima, over bothe \(\varphi\) and \(\theta\). computational considerations may entail the estimation of \(\varphi\) separately from \(\theta\) in a two-step procedure, though in principle this is undesirable because an overall measure allowing for the uncertainty of both \(\hat{\theta}\) and \(\hat{\varphi}\) is then awkward to obtain. In the applications below we found it necessary to use this two-step approach, but then obtained a combined assessment of uncertainty by applying it to bootstrap datasets obtained by resampled subsets of the original ata that could be taken as independent. Initial values for \(\varphi\) can be obtained by maximizing an independent likelihood, which uses the same smooth functions for spatial variation of marginal parameters \(\eta\), \(\tau\), and \(\xi\) as in (2.4), but treats the \(Z\)s as independent standard Frechet variables. Similar computations are needed for likelihoods based on copulas.

2.6.1 Likelihood inference for spatial maxima

We now discuss the computation of the first term in (2.4) in the case of inference based on maxima. The key problem is that this involves \(D\)-fold differentiation of the joint cummulative distribution function (1.8), resulting in a combinatorial explosion. For example, with \(D=3\), we have

\[\begin{equation} f(z_1,z_2,z_3;\theta)=e^{-V}(-V_{123}+V_{1}V_{23}+V_{2}V_{13}+V_{3}V_{12}-V_{1}V_{2}V_{3}) \tag{2.5} \end{equation}\]

using shorthand notation in which

\[ V=V(z_1,z_2,z_3;\theta), V_d=\frac{\partial V (z_1,z_2,z_3;\theta)}{\partial z_d}, V_{d_1,d_2}=\frac{\partial^2 V(z_1,z_2,z_3;\theta)}{\partial_{z_{d_1}}\partial_{z_{d_2}}}, \]

and so forth. The number of terms in the density is the number of partitions of the set \(\mathcal{D}\), with \(\mathcal{D}=\{x_1,x_2,x_3\}\) there are five such partitions, corresponding to the terms on the right-hand side of (2.5), but with \(D=10\) there are around \(10^5\) terms. Thus in realistic setting it is infeasible to compute the full likelihood, and a number of ways to avoid doing so have been proposed.

Composite likelihood inference uses simpler likelihood components. The most common is a pairwise likelihood, in which the components involve only pairs of observations, for example replacing (2.5) by

\[\begin{equation} f(z_1, z_2;\theta)\times f(z_1, z_3;\theta)\times f(z_2, z_3;\theta). \tag{2.6} \end{equation}\]

Here only bivariate exponent functions such as (2.1) and (2.2) and their first and second derivatives are needed. For this approach to be useful, \(\theta\) must be identifiable from the chosen marginal distributions, as is generally the case with Gaussian-based models. Although maximizing a composite likelihood yields consistent estimator, \(\hat{\theta}_{C}\), say, measures of uncertainty and tools for model comparison must compensate for the re-use observations in terms such as (2.6). For example, if \(z_1, z_2, z_3\) were independent, then (2.6) would equal \(\{ f(z_1;\theta)f(z_2;\theta)f(z_3;\theta) \}^2\), i.e., the square of the correct likelihood contribution, and although \(\hat{\theta}_{C}\) would then equal the usual maximum likelihood estimate, standard errors based on the observed information matrix \(\hat{J}\) would be too small by a factor \(\sqrt{2}\).

Standard errors for \(\hat{\theta}_{C}\) can be obtained by resampling or using a sandwich variance matrix \(\hat{J}^{-1}\hat{K}\hat{J}^{-1}\). Suppose that the data fall into independentblocks indexed by \(i\in\mathcal{I}\), and that the \(i\)-th block consists of dependent observations \(z_{i,d}\). In many cases \(\mathcal{I}\) will correspond to data from different years or extreme evnets, assumed to be independent, whereas the data \(z_{i,1}, \ldots, z_{i,D}\) for block \(i\) are likely to be dependent. Then with \(l_{1;d',d}=\log f(z_{i,d'}, z_{i,d};\theta)\) and pairwise likelihood \(\sum_{i}\sum_{d'<d}l_{i;d',d}(\theta)\), we have

\[ \hat{K} = \sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\sum_{d'<d}\frac{\partial l_{i;d',d}(\theta)}{\partial \theta}\frac{\partial l_{i;d',d}(\theta)}{\partial \theta^T}|_{\theta=\hat{\theta}_{C}}, \hat{J}= -\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\sum_{d'<d}\frac{\partial^2 l_{i;d',d}(\theta)}{\partial\theta\partial\theta^T}|_{\theta=\hat{\theta}_{C}}. \]

Data are often missing from some blocks, and then the internal sum is taken over only those pairs available for that block. The matrix \(\hat{K}\) can be unstable, and then resampling of blocks to obtain standard errors is preferable, even though it can be slow.

In some cases the computational burden can be recduced and the statistical properties of \(\hat{\theta}_{C}\) can be enhanced by weighting likelihood constributions \(l_{i;d',d}(\theta)\), for example downweighting pairs that are spatially distant, since these might be expected to contribute less information.

Models are computed using composite likelihood information criterion, \(\text{CLIC}=2\{\text{tr}(\hat{J}^{-1}\hat{K})-\hat{l}_{C}\}\), where \(\hat{l}_{C}\) is the maximum log-composite likelihood; low values of CLIC are preferred. The re-use of observations can lead to very large values of CLIC, and it may be useful to rescale it for comparability with standard information criteria such as AIC; In (2.6), for example, the log likelihood contribution should be halved, and if there were \(D\) maxima, it would be divided by \(D-1\).

A second solution to the explosion of terms in expression such as (2.5) stems from noticing that the terms in expressions such as the right-hand side of (2.5) correspond to different ways in which the extremes can occur: the first corresponds to a single event leading to all three maxima, the last to maxima from three separate events, and the others to the ways in which three maxima might arise from two separate events. Thus if it was known that \(z_1\) arose from one event, whereas \(z_2\) and \(z_3\) occurred together, then the appropriate likelihood contribution would be \(V_{1}V_{23}e^{-V}\) rather than the whole of (2.5). If the required derivatives of \(V\) are available then the resulting likelihood is computationally feasible even in high-dimensional cases, but the resulting maximum likelihood estimators depend on the choice of partition and can be badly biased if this choice is wrong.

In practice, an empirical declustering rule is typically used to estimate the partition, and the approach does not seem to be very robust. It can be improved by estimating the partition in a more formal way, either using a stochastic EM algorithm, or, in a Bayesin context, by including the partition in a Monte-Carlo sampling algorithm, and then integrating over it.

2.6.2 Likelihood inference for spatial threshold exceedances

Analysis of individual events, typiclly those exceeding some suitable threhold, allows more detailed modelling and more precise inferences than analysis of maxima, and is particularly useful when assessing simultaneous risks. In principle, the approach based on the Poisson process approximation using a parametric measure \(\mu_{\theta}(\cdot)\) is straightforward: a set \(\mathcal{E}'\) having finite measure is chosen to select rare events, and then estimation is based on a Poisson process likelihood.

Suppose, for example, that events \(q_1,\ldots, q_n\) have been observed at \(D\) points \(x_1, \ldots, x_D\), so that \(q_j \equiv \{ q_{j}(x_1), \ldots , q_{j}(x_D) \}\), and that \(\mathcal{E}'=\{ q: \rho(q)> 1 \}\) for some functional \(\rho\). Then the selected data will be those \(q_j\) for which \(\rho(q_j)>1\), say \(q_{1}', \ldots, q_{n}'\), and the likelihood is

\[\begin{equation} L_{\text{Pois}}(\theta)=e^{-\mu_{\theta}(\mathcal{E}')}\times \prod_{j=1}^{n'}\dot{\mu}_{\theta}(q_{j}'), \tag{2.7} \end{equation}\]

where \(\dot{\mu}_{\theta}(q)\) denotes the Poisson process intensity evaluated at \(q\). If \(\rho(q)=\sum_{d=1}^{D}\frac{q(x_d)}{u_d}\) for some \(u_1, \ldots, u_D >0\), then \(\mathcal{E}'=\{ (r,w):\sum_{d=1}^{D}r\frac{w(x_d)}{u_d} >1 \}\) and \(\mu_{\theta}(\mathcal{E}')\) is a constant, so only the second term on the right-hand side of (2.7) is needed; it is known asthe sprectral likelihood, though perhaps angular likelihood would be a better term. Its drawback is that the events \(q_{j}'\) thus chosen may have some very small components, making the extremal approxiamtion questionable.

An alternative ensuring that all events are far from the axes wouldbe to take \(\rho(q)=\min_{d}\frac{q(x_d)}{u_d}\), but this can greatly reduce the number of events available for estimation, especially if extremal dependence is weak. We therefore often take \(\rho(q) = \max_{d}\frac{q(x_d)}{u_d}\), but use a censored likelihood to avoid including the exact values of small components, as we now describe. This uses less precise information and thus decreases the precision of our estimates, but it reduces the bias due to inclusion of non-extreme values.

Censored likleihood is most easily explained in the bivariate case, where \(\mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}\) is partitioned into four regions \(\mathcal{R}_{I_1, I_2}\), corresponding to the values of the indicators \(I_1 = I(Q_1 > u_1)\) and \(I_2 = I(Q_2 > u_2)\) of the events that the \(Q_d\) exceed thresholds \(u_d\). If \(I_1 = I_2 = 1\), i.e., both variables exceed the thresholds, then \(q\in\mathcal{R}_{1,1}\), the extremal model is regarded as valid and the likelihood contribution from \(q=(q_1, q_2)\) is \(\dot{\mu}_{\theta}(q)\). If \(I_1 = 1, I_2 = 0\), then \(q\in\mathcal{R}_{1,0}\), so the precise value of \(q_1\) is used but \(q_2\) is left-censored at \(u_2\), giving likelihood contribution \(\int_{0}^{u_2}\dot{\mu}_{\theta}\{ (q_1, y) \} dy\). Likewise when \(I_1 =0, I_2 = 1\), the likelihood contribution is \(\int_{0}^{u_1}\dot{\mu}_{\theta}\{ (x,q_{2} ) \} dx\). If \(I_{1} = I_{2} = 0\), then \(q \in \mathcal{R}_{0,0}\), where the extremal model cannot be trusted, so we use a Poisson process likelihood with region \(\mathcal{E}' = \mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}\backslash \mathcal{R}_{0,0}=\mathcal{E}_{u}\), say, thus having censored contributions from \(\mathcal{R}_{0,1}\) and \(\mathcal{R}_{1,0}\) and uncensored constributions from \(\mathcal{R}_{1,1}\). This likelihood involves computation of \(\mu(\mathcal{E}_{u})=V(u_1, u_2),\) where \(V\) is the exponent function corresponding to \(W(x)\); see (1.8). One can check that \(\dot{\mu}_{\theta}(q) = - \frac{\partial^2 V(q_1, q_2)}{\partial q_1 \partial q_2}\) and that the terms needed for the censored contributions have forms such as \(-\frac{\partial V(u1, q_2)}{\partial q_2}\), with obvious extensions to higher dimensions.
